Use of host plants by Troidini butterflies (Papilionidae, Papilioninae): constraints on host shift

KARINA LUCAS SILVA-BRANDO, VERA NISAKA SOLFERINI
Biological Journal of the Linnean Society, Volume 90, Issue 2, February 2007, Pages 247261, https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8312.2007.00727.x
Published:
31 January 2007
Article history
  • PDF
  • Split View
  • Cite
  • Permissions Icon Permissions
  • Share Icon Share

Abstract

Molecular phylogenetic analyses were conducted to determine relationships and to investigate character evolution for the Troidini/Aristolochia interaction, in an attempt to answer the following questions: (1) what is the present pattern of use of Aristolochia by these butterflies; (2) is the pattern we see today related to the phylogeny of plants or to their chemical composition; (3) can the geographical distribution of Aristolochia explain the host plant use observed today; and (4) how did the interaction between Troidini and Aristolochia evolve? Analyses of character optimization suggest that the current pattern of host plant use of these butterflies does not seem to be constrained by the phylogeny of their food plants, neither by the secondary chemicals in these plants nor by their geographical similarity. The current host plant use in these butterflies seems to be simply opportunistic, with species with a wider geographical range using more species of host plants than those with a more restricted distribution.

Aristolochia, character optimization, chemical similarity, geographical range, molecular phylogeny, pattern approach
Issue Section:
Original Article

INTRODUCTION

The interactions between herbivorous insects and their host plants have been studied for a long time. Many studies have focused particularly on how these interactions have evolved, considering key aspects such as the taxonomic conservatism in host utilization (Bernays, 1998; Janz, Nyblom & Nylin, 2001), and whether there is a trend toward total specialization in this evolutionary history (an evolutionary dead end; Futuyma & Moreno, 1988). Taxonomically-related species of insects frequently feed on taxonomically-related host plants, although precise concordance between insect and plant phylogenies is uncommon (Ehrlich & Raven, 1964; Holloway & Hebert, 1979; Mitter, Farrell & Futuyma, 1991; Janz & Nylin, 1998; Lopez-Vaamonde et al., 2003). Such conservatism in host use is influenced basically by the secondary compounds found in the host plants (Jaenike, 1990; Futuyma, Keese & Scheffer, 1993; Bernays, 1998), and Fraenkel (1959) even proposed that the discriminatory use of certain plants by insects is the raison d'tre of these substances in plants (for a different point of view, see Jones & Firn, 1991). In addition to chemical compounds, other intrinsic and extrinsic factors also appear to constrain the use of host plants by herbivores (Ronquist & Nylin, 1990); these include female ovipositional preferences (Chew & Robbins, 1984) and survival of the larvae on different plants, the pressure of generalist natural enemies (Bernays & Graham, 1988), and the geographical distribution of the species, because a herbivore cannot use a plant species that it never naturally encounters (Pasteels & Rowell-Rahier, 1991; Dobler et al., 1996; Kelley & Farrell, 1998).

The concept that specialization can be an evolutionary dead end has been central in host plant/herbivore evolutionary studies. However, it seems likely that, over evolutionary time, diet breadth in insects has both increased and decreased (Bernays, 1998), sometimes leading to specialization (Moran, 1988; Ronquist & Nylin, 1990; Kelley & Farrell, 1998; Nosil, 2002), and others leading to generalization (Armbruster & Baldwin, 1998; Scheffer & Wiegmann, 2000; Janz et al., 2001). Specialization can be advantageous in several ways. Specialist herbivores may reduce the pathways of incoming chemical signals, leading to economy in neural machinery; for example, by increasing emphasis on only a few chemicals for specific host recognition (Bernays, 1996). In the same way, specialist insects are able to invest less in detoxifying enzymes to struggle with few chemical compounds, instead of a set of different substances (for a review, see Futuyma & Moreno, 1988), although the detoxification capacity may be maintained at the expense of other biological activities (Berenbaum & Zangerl, 1994). In addition, secondary compounds should be poisonous to herbivorous insects that are not adapted to deal with them (Bernays & Graham, 1988). Specialization can even enhance the use of sequestered toxin for defense against predators (Futuyma & Keese, 1992) and, in a competitive environment, specialists are thought to exclude generalists if they use food more efficiently (Futuyma & Moreno, 1988).

Ehrlich & Raven (1964) studied the conservatism in host use by insects and proposed a hypothesis to explain the step-by-step evolution of resistance in plants and adaptations to tolerance of their enemies, which Thompson (1989) called escape-and-radiation coevolution, characterized by periods of absent or reduced interaction between taxa. Despite the idea that coevolution between host plants and herbivores is widespread, other explanations have been proposed to explain the evolution of these associations and Ronquist & Nylin (1990) cite some other coevolutionary models. In the Arms Race type I model (in a microevolutionary time), the effects of the defense (of plants) and counter defense (of herbivores) are less drastic than in the model proposed by Ehrlich & Raven (1964), which Ronquist & Nylin (1990) named Arms Race type II, where defense in plants may not totally exclude insects from them. In the specialization model, the general trend toward specialization in insects occurs independently of evolutionary changes in plants. In the late colonization model (Jermy, 1984, 1993; Percy, Page & Cronk, 2004), colonization occurred in already existing plant groups; therefore, insect groups may be much younger than the plants on which they live. It worth noting that Ehrlich & Raven (1964) are always cited as defenders of the Arm Race model, although, in their paper, they used the example of the Papilionidae/Aristolochiaceae association to state that is likely that the major diversification of Papilionidae took place after the evolution of Aristolochiaceae. Finally, the opportunistic model points out that insects have switched so frequently to new host plants that the historical pattern is lost (Ronquist & Nylin, 1990).

The close association between butterflies of the tribe Troidini (Papilionidae; Papilioninae) and their host plants on the genus Aristolochia L. (Aristolochiaceae, Aristolochioideae) is a suitable model for studies on the evolution of host plant/herbivore relationships. The tribe Troidini is predominantly tropical, with most species concentrated in the lowland forests of Central and South America and in the IndoAustralian region (Weintraub, 1995). The tribe includes 130 species divided into 12 genera, three of which occur in the Neotropics: Battus (11 species), Euryades (two species), and Parides (34 species) (Tyler, Brown & Wilson, 1994). The genus Aristolochia s.l., the largest in the Aristolochiaceae, consists of approximately 500 species centred in tropical regions, with some species inhabiting subtropical and temperate habitats (Kelly & Gonzlez, 2003); approximately 90 species occur in Brazil (Leito & Kaplan, 1992). The species vary from subshrubs to lianas, and the main secondary compounds of these plants are aristolochic acids, aristolactam benzylisoquinoline alkaloids, and mono-, sesqui-, di- and triterpenes, including derived diterpene labdanoic acids (Wu et al., 2004).

The interaction between Troidini and Aristolochia has been used as a classic example of coevolution (Ehrlich & Raven, 1964; Brown et al., 1991). Troidini use almost exclusively plants of Aristolochia, and their larvae are known for sequestering the secondary compounds present in their host plants (Klitzke, 1992), which make them apparently unpalatable to many potential predators and parasitoids (Brower & Brower, 1964; Rothschild et al., 1970); Nishida & Fukami (1989) and Sime (2002) suggested that aristolochic acids may be responsible for the chemical defense in Troidini. The adult butterflies advertise their unpalatability through aposematic coloration, making them notable as unpalatable models in mimicry rings (Tyler et al., 1994).

Brown et al. (1995) demonstrated evidence that basal Troidini use preferentially basal Aristolochia species, whereas derived butterflies also use derived host species, suggesting a high coevolutionary linkage between these butterflies and their host plants. Indeed, the Troidini can vary greatly in their diet breadth (Weintraub, 1995), and the most polyphagous taxa tend to be the butterflies with the widest geographical and ecological ranges. According to Weintraub (1995), monophagy appears to be relatively uncommon at the subgeneric and species level, and it occurs in species with restricted distributions. Recently, Silva-Brando et al. (2005) verified that derived Troidini species use fewer species of Aristolochia as host plants than those species considered basal in their phylogenetic hypothesis; however, these authors highlighted the possibility that such results may simply reflect the geographical distribution of the butterflies instead of showing a trend in the direction of specialization in host plant use.

In the present study, molecular phylogenetic analyses were conducted to determine relationships and to investigate character evolution in the Troidini/Aristolochia interaction, using what Ronquist & Nylin (1990) termed the pattern approach, which is the use of the phylogenies of associated groups to reconstruct the coevolutionary history of the interaction. The main questions concerning the evolution of this interaction are: (1) what is the present pattern of use of Aristolochia by these butterflies; (2) is the pattern we see today related to the phylogeny of plants or to their chemical composition; (3) can the geographical distribution of Aristolochia explain the host plant use observed today; and (4) how did the interaction between Troidini and Aristolochia evolve?

MATERIAL AND METHODS

RELATIONSHIPS AMONG TROIDINI BUTTERFLIES

Molecular phylogeny of Troidini

The study of the evolutionary history of the host plant use of Troidini butterflies focused on those species that occur in south-eastern Brazil, for which almost complete data on host plant use are available, as well as data on host plant secondary compounds (Brown, Damman & Feeny, 1981; Otero & Brown, 1986; Brown et al., 1991, 1995; Morais & Brown, 1991; Klitzke, 1992; Tyler et al., 1994; Klitzke & Brown, 2000; Freitas & Ramos, 2001). The phylogenetic hypothesis for the Troidini used in this study was obtained by a maximum parsimony (MP) analysis of the mitochondrial genes cytochrome oxidase subunits I and II (CO I and CO II) and the nuclear gene elongation factor-1 (EF-1) (Silva-Brando et al., 2005). A total of 2169 bp were sequenced from the mitochondrial DNA and 1161 bp from EF-1. MP analysis was then carried out with PAUP* 4.0b10 (Swofford, 2002). This tree was considered to illustrate the best phylogenetic relationship hypothesis for New World Troidini. Species for which there was no information on host plant use were removed from Silva-Brando et al. (2005: fig. 2).

RELATIONSHIPS AMONG ARISTOLOCHIA SPECIES

Molecular phylogeny of Aristolochia

The phylogenetic hypothesis for the Aristolochia was obtained by MP analysis of two regions: the mat K gene, located within the intron of the chloroplast gene (cpDNA) trn K (Hilu & Liang, 1997), and the region of cpDNA located between the genes trn L (UAA) and trn F (GAA) (Silva-Brando, Solferini & Trigo, 2006). Two thousand two hundred and forty-two nucleotides were sequenced; 1245 from mat K and 997 from the region between trn L-trn F. MP analysis was performed with PAUP* 4.0b10 (Swofford, 2002) on the entire data set, and a consensus tree was generated from the 24 most parsimonious trees (Silva-Brando et al., 2006).

Chemical similarity among Aristolochia species

A dendrogram of chemical similarity (chemogram) of 12 Aristolochia species used as host plants by Troidini butterflies in south-eastern Brazil (Table 1) was constructed using Euclidean distances for similarity determination and Ward's method as a cluster procedure of the relative abundance of 51 compounds eluted in the sesquiterpene region (Silva-Brando et al., 2006). Three main clusters can be recognized: Group 1 is characterized by the high relative abundance of germacrene-D; Group 2 is characterized by a high relative abundance of germacrene-C and Group 3 is characterized by a high relative abundance of Z-caryophyllene. One individual of Aristolochia triangularis and two individuals of Aristolochia esperanzae were pruned from the cluster analysis and from Silva-Brando et al. (2006: fig. 1) because they were not in their main group.

Geographic relationship of Aristolochia species

Distribution maps of each one of the 12 Aristolochia species (Table 1) were created using previously published distributions of these species in south-eastern Brazil (Hoehne, 1942; Capellari., 1991), updated with more recent information from herbarium specimens. The maps were drawn using a baseline map of the south-eastern region (including the states of So Paulo, Rio de Janeiro, Esprito Santo, and Minas Gerais; 40 to 54W; 14 to 26S) on which the locations (cities) of occurrence for each species were recorded.

To estimate the geographical relationships of Aristolochia, a dendrogram based on the similarity of their geographical ranges (biogeogram) was constructed. Following Becerra & Venable (1999), the biogeogram was created using a transparent map of the south-eastern region of Brazil of the same dimensions as the baseline map divided into squares of 0.5 longitude and latitude. This map was superposed over the baseline maps, and the number of squares where each species is present was counted. A matrix of Euclidian distances was created on the basis of the presence and absence of each species in each square, and the dendrogram was constructed with a cluster analysis using Ward's method (Legendre & Legendre, 1998).

HOST PLANT USE PATTERN IN TROIDINI

The approach of Brown et al. (1995) was applied to link the species of butterflies to their host plants to characterize any phylogenetic pattern of host use and host shift, using the molecular phylogenies proposed for Troidini and for Aristolochia. We considered the data of Brown et al. (1995) on the host plant use pattern in Troidini from south-eastern Brazil, including the plant species used preferentially by each species.

CHARACTER OPTIMIZATION

To investigate the importance of the Aristolochia phylogeny in the Troidini evolutionary host shift, character tracing (Maddison & Maddison, 1999) was used. The topology of the Troidini phylogeny was compared with the topology of their host plants, using the MacClade 3.08 program (Maddison & Maddison, 1999) to perform character tracing analyses (Becerra, 1997). The Aristolochia phylogeny (Silva-Brando et al., 2006) was used as a character with six unordered states, corresponding to each clade in the topology; a seventh state was named as the other host plant. Because these butterflies feed on several host plants, each terminal branch resulted in a polymorphic state. To avoid polymorphic codings, each taxon was decomposed in polytomies because the component parts (i.e. the species used by each butterfly) are well known (Maddison & Maddison, 1999).

Although the major objective was to map the host plants onto the terminal branches, to understand the evolution of host plant use, it is necessary to know not only the character state of the living butterflies, but also of their ancestors and, using MacClade, we can also infer the ancestral character state using the MP method (Maddison & Maddison, 1999).

To test whether there is a phylogenetic signal in the character traced, the methodology proposed by Wahlberg (2001) was used, modified from the PTP test described by Faith & Cranston (1991). Three hundred random reshufflings of character states were performed among the fixed terminal taxa, with the equally weighted data set, using the option shuffle in MacClade (Maddison & Maddison, 1999). The probability (P) that the observed pattern does not differ randomly is given by the number of replications as short as or shorter than the tree obtained with the actual data, plus one, divided by the number of replications. Following Faith & Cranston (1991), a significant phylogenetic signal is observed when P < 0.05 and, here, the minimal value should be 0.003.

COMPARISON OF TROIDINI PHYLOGENY WITH THE CHEMOGRAM AND THE BIOGEOGRAM OF ARISTOLOCHIA

To investigate whether the plant chemical similarity and geographical distribution facilitated host shift by Troidini, the topology of the butterflies phylogeny was compared with the topology of the Aristolochia chemogram and biogeogram, using MacClade 3.08 (Maddison & Maddison, 1999) to perform analyses of character tracing. The character chemical similarity has four unordered states, related to the three clusters found in the chemogram of Aristolochia (Silva-Brando et al., 2006) plus state 4 (other host plant). In the same way, as character states, the character geographical similarity has the number of clusters found in the dendogram of Aristolochia obtained by their geographical similarity plus the state other host plant. Analyses of polymorphic species were conducted as for character optimization of Aristolochia phylogeny (i.e. decomposing the taxon). Character states were randomly reshuffled 300 times among the fixed terminal taxa to test whether there is a phylogenetic signal in the characters traced (Wahlberg, 2001), with the equally weighted data set (Maddison & Maddison, 1999).

GEOGRAPHICAL RANGE AND HOST PLANT USE

To test the idea of Weintraub (1995), who suggested that monophagy appears to be relatively unusual at the subgeneric and species levels in Troidini, occurring in species with restricted distributions, maps with the distribution of each one of the 12 species of Troidini from south-eastern Brazil (Table 1) were constructed based on recent data obtained by the project BIOTA-FAPESP Lepidoptera do Estado de So Paulo: diversidade, distribuio e recursos. A transparent map of the south-eastern region of Brazil of the same dimensions as the baseline maps divided into squares of 0.5 longitude and latitude was superposed over those maps, and the number of squares where each species has its distribution known at present were counted. The number of squares occupied by each Troidini was plotted against the number of host plants used by each one, and a linear regression was processed. The same approach was applied to test whether the species of more widely-distributed Aristolochia are more used as host plant than species with a narrower range. This was carried out by counting the number of squares occupied by each species of Aristolochia and these numbers were plotted against the number of Troidini which fed on each one.

RESULTS

HOST PLANT USE PATTERN IN TROIDINI

Considering the phylogenies of Troidini and Aristolochia and linking the species of butterflies to their host plants, resulted in a chaotic picture (Fig. 1). Butterflies occupying different phylogenetic positions use the same host plants indiscriminately. Aristolochia melastoma, for example, is used by Battus polydamas and Battus polystictus, both occupying a basal position within Troidini, and also by Parides neophilus, which occupies the most derived position. Aristolochia esperanzae is also used by butterflies occupying variable phylogenetic positions (Fig. 1).

Figure 1.
Open in new tabDownload slide

Interactions between New World Troidini butterflies and their larval host plants on the genus Aristolochia in south-eastern Brazil. Phylogenies are based on molecular data: cytochrome oxidase subunits I and II and the nuclear gene elongation factor-1 for butterflies, and mat K and the region between trn F-trn L for plants. Strongest lines indicate the preferred host plant (Brown et al., 1995).

Battus polydamas and Parides anchises, the most polyphagous Troidini studied here, show different patterns of host plant utilization. Battus polydamas use almost all Aristolochia species available, without any preference (Brown et al., 1995), and in all clades. Parides anchises also feed on Aristolochia species of all clades, but uses preferentially three species which appeared together in the same clade (Aristolochia cymbifera, Aristolochia galeata and A. esperanzae) (Fig. 1).

CHARACTER OPTIMIZATION

Tracing the major clades of the Aristolochia phylogeny onto the Troidini phylogeny showed the widespread use of host plants in all clades (Fig. 2). According to our results, the host plant used by the ancestors of both Battus and Parides may have belonged to the clade joining Aristolochia macroura, A. cymbifera, A. galeata and A. esperanzae. Currently, all Parides use Aristolochia species belonging to this clade, except Parides tros and Parides panthonus jaguarae (Fig. 2). However, the distribution of this character does not seem to be determined by the topology of Troidini (P = 1.0). Decomposing each taxon instead of using polymorphisms did not change the number of steps in the final tree or the results of the phylogenetic signal analyses. Nevertheless, it made the picture more visually informative.

Figure 2.
Open in new tabDownload slide

Comparison between Troidini and Aristolochia phylogenies. The six clades of Aristolochia (A) are traced onto the Troidini phylogenetic tree (B), with as many polytomies as the number of host plants used by each butterfly species.

COMPARISON OF TROIDINI PHYLOGENY WITH THE CHEMOGRAM AND THE BIOGEOGRAM OF ARISTOLOCHIA

The comparison between the phylogeny of Troidini and the chemogram of Aristolochia showed that the ancestors of Battus and Parides may have fed on host plants belonging to the germacrene-D group (Group 1), and that the plants with a higher relative abundance of this compound are still used by these butterflies (Fig. 3). On the other hand, both Parides ascanius and Parides zacynthus feed exclusively on plants with high amounts of germacrene-C (Group 2; Fig. 3).

Figure 3.
Open in new tabDownload slide

Comparison between Troidini phylogeny and Aristolochia chemogram. The three clusters of Aristolochia (A) are traced onto the Troidini phylogenetic tree (B), with as many polytomies as the number of host plants used by each butterfly species.

The cluster analysis with Ward's method identified four main groups of Aristolochia species, according to the degree of similarity of their geographical ranges (Fig. 4). Group 1 includes Aristolochia arcuata, A. melastoma, Aristolochia gigantea, A. cymbifera and A. galeata, all widely distributed, mainly south east of So Paulo and Minas Gerais, and near the city of Rio de Janeiro. Group 2, composed of Aristolochia chamissonis, Aristolochia paulistana and A. triangularis, includes mostly species whose geographical range includes the South of So Paulo. Group 3 contains Aristolochia cynanchifolia, A. macroura and Aristolochia elegans, and includes species occurring exclusively in Rio de Janeiro (cynanchifolia), in the North of Minas Gerais (elegans), and in coastal So Paulo, Esprito Santo, and Rio de Janeiro (macroura). Group 4 is composed exclusively of A. esperanzae, the only species inhabiting the north east of So Paulo and the west of Minas Gerais. Character tracing of the geographical similarity of Aristolochia onto the Troidini phylogeny showed that the host plant used by the ancestor of Battus and that of Parides may have come from different clusters (Fig. 4). The ancestor of Battus may have once fed on host plants from Group 1. On the other hand, the host plant used by the ancestor of Parides may have belonged to Group 3, composed of plants with a less uniform distribution, and with two species showing a coastal range. At present, almost all Troidini feed on plants in Group 1, with species showing a broad distribution. Four species of Troidini from south-eastern Brazil (B. polydamas, Parides bunichus, Parides agavus and P. anchises) use Aristolochia species from all geographical ranges. Otherwise, B. polystictus use host plants almost exclusively from Group 1, with one representative of Group 2 (Fig. 4). For both optimizations, the phylogenetic signal over the topology of Troidini was not significant (P = 0.25 for chemical similarity and P = 0.46 for geographical similarity).

Comparison between Troidini phylogeny and Aristolochia biogeogram. The four clusters of Aristolochia (A) are traced onto the Troidini phylogenetic tree (B), with as many polytomies as the number of host plants used by each butterfly species.

GEOGRAPHICAL RANGE AND HOST PLANT USE

The numer of host plants used by Troidini butterflies is significantly affected by their distribution (r2 = 0.8286, P < 0.001; Fig. 5). Thus, butterflies with a larger distribution use a higher number of hosts; however, the most widely-distributed host plants are not most consumed by Troidini. The relation between the number of squares occupied by each species of Aristolochia and the number of Troidini which feed on each one is not significative (r2 = 0.0854, P = 0.357) (Fig. 6).

DISCUSSION

HOST PLANT PHYLOGENY CONSTRAINTS

We did not find any strong indication that basal Troidini use basal Aristolochia, or that derived species of these butterflies feed on derived species of their host plants (Figs 1, 2). There appears to be no current pattern of host plant utilization based on the phylogenies of Troidini and Aristolochia. This does not agree with the proposal of Brown et al. (1995), who suggested a coevolutionary linkage between these butterflies and their host plants. Becerra (1997) found a weak influence of host plant phylogeny on the evolution of host use in the Blepharida/Bursera interaction. On the other hand, Farrell & Mitter (1998) found an almost complete correspondence between the phylogenies of Tetraopes beetles and Asclepias used as host plants.

Intriguingly, the comparison between the phylogenies of Troidini and Aristolochia have shown that the host plant used by the ancestors of Battus and Parides may have come from the clade joining A. macroura, A. cymbifera, A. galeata, and A. esperanzae (Fig. 2). Only A. macroura has aristolochic acids (AAs) in the leaves, whereas the other three species have mainly labdanoic acids (LAs) (Klitzke, 1992; Leito & Kaplan, 1992). It was expected that the host plant used by the ancestor of Troidini could contain exclusively AAs in their leaves, but our results suggest that, possibly, the ancestral host plant could have LAs. According to the proposal of coevolution between Troidini and Aristolochia (Brown et al., 1991), these plants may have changed their classes of chemical compounds as a consequence of herbivore pressure. Hence, derived species of Aristolochia may have lost AAs and acquired other defenses, such as LAs, to deter species of herbivores specialized on Aristolochiaceae, which contain AAs. The preferential use of species with LAs by P. anchises can support the hypothesis of coevolution proposed by Brown et al. (1991), because this is a derived species within Troidini (Silva-Brando et al., 2005). However, in the present study, we found that the use of plants containing LAs may have arisen early in Troidini, at least for those species from south-eatern Brazil. Although this may be true, a consistent body of data has shown evidence that the use of plants with AAs is physiologically more advantageous for these butterflies. Species of Troidini fed with leaves of A. galeata (with LAs) consumed less of these leaves and showed a smaller relative growth than those fed with Aristolochia species containing only AAs (Klitzke, 1992).

A possible explanation for the incogruences found between our results and those found by Klitzke (1992) could be the different approach used in each study. Klitzke (1992) tested, among other things, the consumption of different species of Aristolochia by Troidini, showing that some species are more consumed than others, and correlated these results with the chemical compounds found in Aristolochia. Here, we used a phylogenetic approach based only on the presence/absence of each species of Aristolochia in the diet of each species of Troidini; however, we did not consider whether one species is more used than others. Consequently, possibly some records could show suboptimal use of food plants because polyphagous species may feed on less preferred host plants due to the lack of their usual food plant at a particular place and time (Fox & Morrow, 1981; Bernays & Graham, 1988).

The use of plants with AAs may also have been promoted by the pressure of natural enemies, which may also have played a role in constraining the host shift in Troidini. Although this tribe produce indogenous toxins kept in their osmeterial glands (Berenbaum, 1995), AAs sequestered from their host plants can be found in all fases of the development of some species, even in the osmeterial secretion (Nishida & Fukami, 1989). These compounds are believed to protect Troidini butterflies from predation (Nishida & Fukami, 1989), although new evidence suggests that AAs alone are not very effective in avoiding predation of B. polydamas larvae in field bioassays (J. R. Trigo, pers. com.).

Ancestor reconstructions are estimates based on data from extant terminals, and the parsimony method seeks to reconstruct ancestral states by choosing the states at each internal node that require the minimal number of steps on the tree (Maddison & Maddison, 1999). Thus, the widespread use of plants belonging to the clade of species showing LAs in their leaves must have resulted in this state at the ancestral node. We can say with confidence that, currently, the presence of AAs and LAs does not appear to constrain the use of Aristolochia by Troidini, but how this use evolved is a matter for future studies.

Within Papilionidae, an association with Aristolochiaceae is not exclusive to the Troidini tribe (Weintraub, 1995). The Zerynthiini tribe in the subfamily Parnassinae feed exclusively on Aristolochiaceae, as well as the genus Archon in the tribe Parnasiini. According to Miller (1987), the most parsimonious explanation is the independent origin of the Aristolochiaceae association in Parnassinae and Papilioninae. Unfortunately, the main difficulty in performing wider analysis about the evolution of the interaction between Papilionidae and Aristolochiaceae has been the lack of resolution in host data (Weintraub, 1995).

HOST PLANT SECONDARY CHEMICALS CONSTRAINTS

The analyses of character optimization of the chemical similarity of Aristolochia in the phylogeny of Troidini did not show a significant phylogenetic signal, and it is difficult to interpret the role of the sesquiterpene similarity of Aristolochia in the host shift by Troidini because these butterflies feed on a large number of host plants. Janz & Nylin (1998) found that growth form is the more conservative aspect of host association between Papilinoidea and their host plants, suggesting that other factors rather than plant chemistry may have an important role in shaping these associations. On the other hand, Becerra & Venable (1999) found that host plant chemistry best explains the overall pattern of host shifts by Blepharida beetles, and Wahlberg (2001) also found that host plant chemistry is a more conservative trait than host plant taxonomy in the evolutionary history of host plant use in the tribe Melitaeini. Berenbaum (2001) also suggested that chemical similarity in Apiaceae, rather than geographical proximity or phylogenetic relationship, is the most probable basis for the observed host plant shifts.

Behavioural and physiological facilitation may have constrained a host shift in these butterflies (Berenbaum, 1995), although both alternatives need to be studied more. Patterns of chemical similarity among host plants of swallowtail butterflies indicate that plant chemistry has channeled host shifts through behavioural facilitation, metabolic preadaptation, or dependence on particular plant compounds for growth, survival, or reproduction (Feeny, 1995). Alternatively, some insects may be physiologically dependent upon the presence of particular chemicals to elict feeding behaviour (Berenbaum, 1995). Troidini butterflies may be restricted to Aristolochia due to an inability to process toxins in other plant families.

The presence of a host plant containing germacrene-D as its main sesquiterpene in the ancestral node of Troidini can be explained by the preferred use of plants with this character. Only two species of Parides, P. ascanius and P. zacynthus, do not feed on host plants containing germacrene-D at high relative abundance (Fig. 3). Pressure of pollinators may have governed the evolution of different sesquiterpenes in Aristolochia, although any evidence for this has not been demonstrated until now. Possibly, besides their differential role in attracting pollinator insects, these sesquiterpenes can differentially attract other floral visitors; that is, P. ascanius and P. zacynthus can be mostly attracted to plants containing a high relative abundance of germacrene-C. The same can be said about Battus crassus and P. panthonus jaguarae, which use Aristolochia plants belonging exclusively to the germacrene-D group.

Although the sesquiterpene composition has worked well as a chemotaxonomic marker to separate Aristolochia species (Silva-Brando et al., 2006), there may not be enough chemical difference among these species to constrain their use by Troidini. The main sesquiterpenes found on plants studied here are quite similar among species (Silva-Brando et al., 2006). We may suggest that, once the initial chemical barrier for using plants in the genus Aristolochia was overcome, it was likely that all available species were used due to their chemical similarity, and a possible metabolic preadaptation (Feeny, 1995). This assumption partly agrees with the coevolutionary hypothesis of Ehrlich & Raven (1964) who suggested that some butterfly groups may have found a free adaptive zone to radiate on plants chemically defended against other herbivore insects, although the role of these insects in the radiation of their host plants may have been insignificant (Thompson, 1989). Weintraub (1995) suggested that colonization events are relatively frequent in Troidini.

HOST PLANT GEOGRAPHICAL CONSTRAINTS

An alternative to host shifts among phylogenetic or chemically related host plants is that insects may have shifted among hosts within a biogeographical area because it may be easier to change the host plant if the geographical range of the new host is similar to that of the old host (Becerra & Venable, 1999). In the present study, we did not find a significant phylogenetic signal in the character optimization of the geographical similarity of Aristolochia and the phylogeny of Troidini, and the same result was found by Becerra & Venable (1999), who proposed that geographical similarity is less important to host shifts in Blepharida beetles than the chemistry of their host plants.

The significant positive correlation between the geographical range of Troidini and the number of host plants used as food (Fig. 5) agrees with the proposal of Weintraub (1995) that the most polyphagous Troidini are those with the broadest geographical range. However, the most widely-distributed host plants are not necessarily most used by these butterflies (Fig. 6). This indicates that the butterflies may not occupy the entire range of their host plants. In this way, host plant availability cannot be considered a constraint to Troidini host shift, and other biotic or abiotic factors can provide different selective pressures at different times (Quinn, Gaston & Roy, 1997).

CONCLUSIONS

The present pattern of host plant use by Troidini does not seem to be constrained by the phylogeny of their food plants, neither by the secondary chemicals in these plants nor by their geographical similarity. In general, the New World Troidini butterflies studied here feed on both basal and derived species of Aristolochia, species with or without AAs in their leaves, and even species showing only LAs. In addition, these butterflies accept Aristolochia species showing distinct sesquiterpene patterns equally well. Furthermore, with the exception of strictly monophagous species, all Troidini use Aristolochia species with different geographical ranges. The current host plant use in these butterflies appears to be mostly opportunistic, with species with a wider geographical range using more species of host plants than those with a more restrict distribution (Weintraub, 1995). This behaviour might merely mirror the available choice and abundance of different host plants in different regions within a butterfly's geographical range, even if these plants are not phylogenetically or chemically related (Fox & Morrow, 1981; Rowell, 1985; Pasteels & Rowell-Rahier, 1991; Percy et al., 2004), showing the label pattern suggested by Bernays & Graham (1988) for host plant use. In this way, the high host plant fidelity at tribal level is lost at lower taxonomic levels.

Such a resource availability pattern was found by Gomez-Zurita, Juan & Petitpierre (2000), who proposed that food specialization in Timarcha is dependent on geographical distribution. Oreina species provide an example of host plant choice governed by available options rather than by plant relatedness and chemical similarity (Dobler et al., 1996). In the same way, Pasteels & Rowell-Rahier (1991) affirmed that the frequent shift of host plants by leaf beetles of the tribe Chrysomelini appears to be opportunistic and not governed by chemical similarity among host plants or by phylogenetic parallels between the beetles and their host plants. The possible exception, in Troidini, to this availability model must be P. ascanius. This species is a strict specialist on A. macroura, although other Aristolochia species are available in its habitats (Otero & Brown, 1986); however, the host plant interactions in this species could be an example of habitat fidelity rather than host fidelity (Dobler et al., 1996) because it is specialized not only to its host plant, but also to the physical and biotic environment where this plant grows (Bernays, 1996).

Several reasons could have led to regional differences in host plant preferences in Troidini, such as the presence of a competitor for food, the regional quality of plants, the difference in sense organs of the insects, behavioural differences or the developmental stage, as well environmental factors, such as seasonality and temperature (Schoonhoven, Jermy & van Loon, 1998). In addition, as in all family Papilionidae, ecological opportunism may have been constrained by past evolutionary history, such as adaptations of insect life history, form, and function to a plant's food value, microclimate, phenology, dispersion, and predator fauna (Feeny, 1995).

Our results indicate that change and the potential for changing may be great in the Troidini/Aristolochia interaction. Plants and butterflies should be under constant selective pressure, and it is expected that interactions are being renewed at the same rhythm, in a dynamic ecological process. Thus, the data collected over time could reveal the picture of interactions to be even more chaotic.
